The user updates his self-description as follows: I now gravitate toward warm, organic classic‑rock and Southern‑rock sounds — roomy analog mixes with natural ambience, clear rhythm‑section weight, soulful lead vocals and guitar interplay (slide, twin leads, tasteful extended solos) that breathe and propel the groove. I enjoy records that allow live band dynamics and improvisational flair so long as melody and momentum remain intact.  
I still favor song‑forward compilations and classic‑rock/AOR snapshots with memorable hooks, strong melodies, guitar‑forward arrangements, and tactile texture; concise sequencing is welcome but not at the expense of feel. Thoughtful mastering that preserves dynamics and separation is important.  
Dislikes: over‑polished stadium gloss, hyper‑compressed/bright mixes and excessive vocal‑stacking that flatten character; formulaic, antiseptic production that kills groove; aimless noodling without melodic purpose; muddy, poorly balanced mixes and overly intimate, breathy close‑miked vocals that expose rather than enhance the song.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Warm, analog Southern‑rock set with roomy drums, clear rhythm‑section weight, tactile bass and natural ambience; soulful lead vocals, tasteful slide and twin‑lead guitar interplay, concise song selection and thoughtful mastering that preserves dynamics and separation for live‑band feel.

